# Summary

As a project and team scales, it is important to have an organized Git workflow. For that, Falls Digital recommends implementing the Gitflow workflow. Utilizing Gitflow will keep updates separate and organized by using different branching techniques such as feature branches, hotfix branches and release branches. Additionally, the use of two primary branches, develop and master act as staging and production zones for safer releases. This document will outline the recommended process for Cleveland Clinic to leverage the Gitflow workflow further standardizing its approach to development.

# Quick Notes

This section outlines the main terminology and provides a handy reference section to identify the purpose of the different types of branches used within the Gitflow process.

## Branches

### Main branches (Master, Develop and Release)

- Master: The master branch is generally equivalent to the production branch. This branch should remain clean and only pushed to for hotfixes or completed launches.  All commits to this branch are automatically deployed to production.
- Develop: The develop branch is the workhorse branch; most updates are made and merged within this branch. This branch is used as an integration branch.  All commits to this branch are automatically deployed to dev.
- Release: The release branch contains all completed features that are ready in QA and acts as a staging branch for master.  All commits to this branch are automatically deployed to QA.

### Feature Branches

Feature branches are the workhorse of the Gitflow process. Every time a new project is started, a new feature branch should be created. Feature branches should:

- Branch off of develop, not master
- Get merged into develop when complete

### Hotfix Branches

Hot fix branches are intended to be used sparingly, for small urgent updates that will be pulled into other existing branches as soon as the fix is complete. Hot fix branches should:

- Branch off of master
- Are for fixing high priority bugs
- Get merged into develop and master when complete

## Branch Protection

### Code Reviews

Code reviews are helpful to enforce code standards, quality, and developer awareness.  We require all code to be reviewed and approved before it can be merged into develop.  Currently, code reviews are only formally enforced in repos hosted on GitHub.  For repos hosted on the private Git server, the code review process should still be followed.

### Push Restrictions

Only repo administrators are permitted to push commits into develop, release or master

## Repo Cleanup

### Delete feature, and hotfix branches.

- **** In order to prevent a messy repository, it&#39;s always a good practice to keep things clean by deleting feature and hotfix branches once they have been merged and the sprint is completed.

# How it Works

### Create a develop branch from master

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

This branch will contain the complete history of the project; whereas master will contain an abridged version.

### Developers begin new features

Feature branches branch off of develop and are used for all new features and any updates that aren&#39;t hot fixes.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

### A developer finishes their feature and issues a pull request to merge back into develop

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

_Commits into the develop branch will immediately trigger a Team City build and deploy to the dev environment._

### A developer prepares a release by merging develop into release

This branch is a place to clean up the release, test, update the documentation, and do any other kind of preparation for the upcoming release. _Commits into the release branch will immediately trigger a Team City build and deploy to the QA environment._  Bugs found during QA should be fixed in the following manner:

- **** Create branch off of release
- **** Commit and push the fix to origin
-
****
 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Issue pull request to merge into the release branch


Issue pull request to merge into the release branch

### A developer finishes the release

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once the release is complete, merge the release branch into master. Note, the release branch act as a buffer between feature development (develop) and public releases (master). Whenever a commit is merged into master, the commit should be tagged for easy reference (a version number is a good way to tag master branch commits). The release branch will also need to be merged back into develop to maintain congruency.  _Commits into the master branch will immediately trigger a Team City build and deploy to the author, preview, and production environments._

### End-user discovers a bug

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Developer branches off of master to easily address bug. The developer commits the changes then merges back into master.

Like release branches, hotfix branches contain important updates that need to be included in develop, so the developer needs to perform that merge as well.

# Gitflow with SourceTree

## Setup

One of the positive aspects of using SourceTree is it will simplify the Gitflow process. Below are screenshots of going through the Gitflow process with SourceTree.

To instantiate the Gitflow process, simply click the &#39;Gitflow&#39; icon. Falls recommends sticking with the default naming convention. Click &#39;OK&#39;.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Starting a new Feature

Now that the master and develop branches have been setup, work can begin on a new feature. To start a new feature, click &#39;Gitflow&#39; again and it will automatically assume a new feature branch is to be created.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

After starting the new feature branch and entering its name, development can begin. Note, there can be as many commits as necessary on a feature branch. The idea is to keep project work separate and organized.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once the necessary commits have been made, it&#39;s time to merge the feature into develop and close the feature. Click &#39;Gitflow&#39; again to finish the feature branch. This will merge the changes into develop and delete the feature branch, putting the Gitflow process back to working in Develop

## Release

Once the updates are ready to push live, the next step is to merge develop into the release branch.

After all of the changes have been committed to the release branch, the release branch will be merged into master to begin the deploy.  At this point verify that the release branch is also merged back into develop.

## Hotfix

Finally, let&#39;s assume an urgent bug/hotfix is logged and needs to be taken care of ASAP. In this case it is recommended to branch directly off of master.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Again, navigate back to the Gitflow menu and choose &#39;Start a New Hotfix&#39;. Name the hotfix, preferably with an issue name or number and make the changes on that branch. Once everything has been committed, choose &#39;Finish Current&#39; to merge and delete the branch.

# Code Reviews with GitHub

## Creating a Pull Request

GitHub greatly simplifies the Pull Request process. Below are screenshots of creating a Pull Request inside a GitHub repo.

To create a Pull Request, simply click the &#39;New pull request&#39; button on the repo home page.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

On the following page, choose the base branch (develop or release) and the head branch (the branch you want to merge into develop or release).

Enter an appropriate title for the pull request, and provide a description of the changes included.  You may also request specific reviewers, but notifications will be sent to all collaborators on the repo.

## Reviewing a Pull Request

Pull requests can be viewed by clicking on the &quot;Pull Requests&quot; tab.  This will provide links to all open pull requests.  Clicking on one will take you to the details of that request.  Here you will be able to leave comments, approve the request or request changes.  Once an approval is received, the pull request can be merged into the base branch.
